''{{PAGENAME}}'' is one of the {{ill|Kujūku Ōji|fr|Kujūkuōji|ja|九十九王子|lt=99 ōji Shrines}} on the [[Kumano Kodō]]. <!--PAGENAME magic word should be substituted in the future when this is moved to its final pagename. This was added to a few pages not created on Feb 8 because they were very barren and this gives context to the fact that they are in a large group of pages all to be translated more or less as a group similar to the Ise Shrines--> ==Overview== [[File:Site of Asahi-sinmeisha, Sakaguchi-Oji.JPG|thumb|Site of Asahi Shinmeisha, Sakaguchi Ōji]] '''Sakaguchi Ōji''' ('''さかぐちおうじ''') was the second {{ill|Kumano Kyuju-kū Ōji|ja|九十九王子}} shrine along the {{ill|Kumano Kodo|ja|熊野古道}} pilgrimage route. The shrine no longer exists. Its presumed site is around {{ill|Minami-Oe Park|ja|南大江公園}} in {{ill|Kanzaki-chō|ja|神崎町}}, {{ill|Chūō-ku, Osaka|ja|中央区 (大阪市)}}, {{ill|Osaka City|ja|大阪市}}.
There used to be a shrine called {{ill|Asahi Shinmeigū|ja|朝日神明宮}} in this area, which has since been relocated to {{ill|Konohana-ku, Osaka|ja|此花区}}. Currently, a small shrine dedicated to {{ill|Tanukizaka Daimyōjin|ja|狸坂大明神}} stands within Minami-Oe Park. Nearby is the {{ill|Enoki Daimyōjin|ja|榎木大明神}}, considered a remnant of the Ōji site. Enoki Daimyōjin is a small shrine enshrining a sacred tree, believed to be an {{ill|enoki|ja|エノキ}} (Chinese hackberry), and is located just south of Minami-Oe Park. Some also consider it an ancient {{ill|Ichirizuka|ja|一里塚}} (milestone mound).
However, botanical analysis has revealed that the sacred tree is actually an {{ill|enju|ja|槐}} (Japanese pagoda tree).
