aisha]]） | style="background:#ccffcc" |[[湯の峰王子|湯ノ峯王子]] goodbye $1（[[:en:Kumano Hayatama Taisha|Hayatama Taisha]]） | style="background:#ccffcc" |[[浜王子]] | style="background:#ccffcc" |[[佐野王子 (新宮市)|佐野王子]] | style="background:#ccffcc" |[[熊野三所大神社|浜の宮王子]] |- | style="background:#ccffcc" |[[市野々王子]] | style="background:#ccffcc" |[[多富気王子]] goodbye $1（{{ill|--><!-- | style="background:#ccffcc" |[[九十九王子 (日高町)#小中王子|小中王子]] | style="background:#ccffcc" |[[九十九王子 (日高町)#比井王子|比井王子]] | style="background:#ccffcc" |[[九十九王子 (日高町)#松原王子|松原王子]] --><!--Sakaguchi Ōji--><!--Sakaguchi Ōji--> [[Category:大阪市中央区の建築物]] [[Category:大阪市中央区の歴史]]

'''Sakaguchi Ōji''' is one of the {{ill|Kujūku Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|fr|Kujūku Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|ja|九十九王子|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|2=ja|3=九十九王子|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|4=fr|5=Kujūkuōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|lt=99 ōji Shrines|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kujūku Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|13=User:Immanuelle/Kujūku Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|qq=}} on the [[Kumano Kodō]].
==Overview== [[File:Site of Asahi-sinmeisha, Sakaguchi-Oji.JPG|thumb|Site of Asahi Shinmeisha, Sakaguchi Ōji]] '''Sakaguchi Ōji''' ('''さかぐちおうじ''') was the second {{ill|Kumano Kyuju-kū Ōji|ja|九十九王子|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|2=ja|3=九十九王子|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|4=fr|5=Kujūkuōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Kyuju-kū Ōji|13=User:Immanuelle/Kujūku Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|qq=}} shrine along the [[:en:Kumano Kodō|Kumano Kodō]] pilgrimage route. The shrine no longer exists. Its presumed site is around {{ill|Minami-Oe Park|ja|南大江公園|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Minami-Oe Park|qq=}} in [[:en:Kōzaki|Kanzaki-chō]], [[:en:Chūō-ku, Osaka|Chūō-ku, Osaka]], [[:en:Osaka|Osaka City]].
There used to be a shrine called {{ill|Asahi Shinmeigū|ja|朝日神明宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Asahi Shinmeigū|qq=}} in this area, which has since been relocated to [[:en:Konohana-ku, Osaka|Konohana-ku, Osaka]]. Currently, a small shrine dedicated to {{ill|Tanukizaka Daimyōjin|ja|狸坂大明神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tanukizaka Daimyōjin|qq=}} stands within Minami-Oe Park. Nearby is the {{ill|Enoki Daimyōjin|ja|榎木大明神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Enoki Daimyōjin|qq=}}, considered a remnant of the Ōji site. Enoki Daimyōjin is a small shrine enshrining a sacred tree, believed to be an [[:en:Celtis sinensis|enoki]] (Chinese hackberry), and is located just south of Minami-Oe Park. Some also consider it an ancient [[:en:Ichirizuka|Ichirizuka]] (milestone mound).
However, botanical analysis has revealed that the sacred tree is actually an {{ill|enju|ja|槐|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/enju|qq=}} (Japanese pagoda tree).
[[File:TanukizakaDaimyojin.JPG|thumb|Tanukizaka Daimyōjin]]
